name: EYESTONE B.A.S.E. CAMP
details:
Our Before and After School Programs are activity based and support classroom learning, providing help with homework, snacks, arts & crafts, sports, science & music activities. Through these programs children develop academic, socialization, arts, athletic, and communication skills which instill them with the confidence and ability to succeed in their school and community.

Programs are tailored to meet each school’s unique requests, and to identify and respond to each child’s needs. A broad range of experience, talent, and skills allow our diverse staff to build programs in collaboration with school staff that respond to changing demo-graphics, backgrounds, and academic levels.

Summer Camp is an “all about fun” program that also focuses on preventing “summer slide” (a loss of previous year’s learning) and returning children to the classroom in the fall at their grade level and ready to learn. The program offers a “green” environment with children learning sustainable living practices such as gardening, composting, and recycling. Partial and full Scholarships make these experiences available to children who would not otherwise have them.

School Out Days (SOD) offers special activities on those days when school is not in session such as teacher conference days, in-service days, holiday breaks, and spring break. SOD’s are held at one or two school sites accessible to all students. During this time, the children focus on special themes such as arts, sciences, sports, music, and drama. They also take field trips and periodically hear speakers and instructors regarding particular topics of interest.

name: CIRCULO MONTESSORI DE TLATELOLCO
details: Círculo Montessori (Círculo). Circulo is a dual language pre-k and elementary program, based on Maria Montessori’s theories of child development, in which children learn in a “prepared environment” designed to maximize independent learning and exploration. The prepared environment includes five distinct areas: practical life, sensorial learning, mathematics, language arts, and cultural activities. Hands-on experiential learning, such as that used in a Montessori classroom, has proven very successful in dual language settings to help students grasp meaning from experience as well as from language. Dual language programs have also been found to enhance students’ self-esteem and academic achievement.

name: THE SALVATION ARMY - RED SHIELD CENTER
THE PRE-SCHOOL AT ROCKY MOUNTAIN ACADEMY
details: The Preschool at Rocky Mountain Academy of Evergreen is a tuition-based preschool that delivers the preschool sequence of the Core Knowledge Curriculum, which is the same curriculum that Rocky Mountain Academy of Evergreen, a K-8 tuition-free public charter school, uses.  The two schools collaborate to provide cohesion for families with children that attend both schools and seamless transition for families whose children move from the preschool to the K-12 campus.  With that said, the two schools are separate organizations and are managed completely separately.  Children who attend our preschool do not receive priority status when enrolling at Rocky Mountain Academy of Evergreen’s K-8 program.  Only students with siblings enrolled at the K-12 campus receive priority status, as is stipulated in RMAE’s enrollment procedure.  Attending preschool, whether it is our preschool or any preschool, is not a prerequisite to enrolling in RMAE’s kindergarten or kindergarten in any Jeffco Public School.

name: COUNTRYSIDE MONTESSORI PRESCHOOL
details:
We feel strongly that children enrolled in full time care are entitled to the highest quality program possible.  Countryside Montessori offers a full-day Montessori program for children 2 ½-6 years in a home-like, country atmosphere.  

We do not segregate our day into a Montessori period and a daycare period. Rather, we’ve integrated our day into a flowing schedule of activities blending the Montessori curriculum with art, Spanish, sign language, cooking, sewing, gardening, animal care, movement, pretend play, carpentry and field trips.The children are with the same consistent, mature staff all day.

Dr. Maria Montessori believed that no human being is educated by another person. He must do it himself or it will never be done. A truly educated individual continues learning long after the hours and years he spends in the classroom because he is motivated from  within by a natural curiosity and love for knowledge. Therefore, Dr. Montessori believed that the goal of early childhood education should not be to fill the child with facts from a pre-selected course of studies, but rather to cultivate his own natural desire to learn.”

details:

Our program separates children into age-appropriate groups, teaching social skills, conflict resolution, sharing and respect.  We fine-tune motor skills, conduct science experiments, and explore the arts.  We teach Spanish, create music and expand our imaginations. As children progress into Pre-Kindergarten classes, we introduce math, phonics and pre-reading programs, enabling children to transition into Elementary School with all the skill sets they need.

name: ST LUKES EPISCOPAL PRESCHOOL
details:
St. Luke’s Preschool is a professionally staffed, state-licensed outreach of the church that has been serving families in Fort Collins and the surrounding area for more than 40 years. Our mission is to provide a high-quality early childhood education in a safe, nurturing and stimulating environment that will prepare your child for kindergarten and later learning. We foster a joy for learning while respecting each child's social, emotional, physical and cognitive growth and development.

We offer three class choices. Our classes begin the Tuesday after Labor Day and end the Friday before Memorial Day. In general, we follow the Poudre School District (PSD) calendar for days off. We also follow the PSD kindergarten eligibility cutoff date of September 15. Primary classes are for children who will be three years old.; our pre-kindergarten classes are for children who will be four years old. If you wish to enroll your child and he or she will turn three or four after September 15 but by October, please call to discuss your child's readiness for our program.

name: ALSUP / ILC
details:
We are looking forward to what I know will be a successful school year for the 2011-2012 calendar. Our academic focus continues to be on reading, writing, math and science with an emphasis on English Language Development when needed.  All Adams14 students receive a minimum of 90 minutes of direct reading instruction, and 60 minutes of writing and math instruction per day.  In addition, as an IB World School all students participate in six units of inquiry thoroughout the year which adds an international perspective to their learning each day.

        We also continue to incorporate more wellness initiatives into our building, including fresh fruits and veggies for all students twice per week and increasing the amount of daily physical activity children receive both outside and inside the classroom.  We are also proud of our annual youth-run farmer's markets that will be held again this fall.  Parents, students and community members can purchase fresh produce right here at Alsup, with a portion of that produce provided from our very own school garden!

         Through our partnership with the University of Colorado at Denver we currently have eight teacher candidates working with our teachers.  With the support of our UCD site professor, Pam McEwan, we are able to provide additional academic support for our students.

          I am honored to have the opportunity to be the principal here at Alsup IB World School and I cannot tell you enough how proud I am to be part of this organization.  The teaching staff, support staff, family members and of course, the students make this the greatest, most satisfying place to work.  Please email me or call if you have any questions or concerns at: tlbenallo@adams14.org and/or 303-288-6865.  Thank you for sharing your children with us every day!

name: CHERRY HILLS VILLAGE EXTENDED CHILDCARE SVCS
details:
Cherry Hills Village Elementary began as a one-room school in 1886. It was originally named Breene Avenue School and was built on a dirt path that later became Quincy Avenue. A handful of students from surrounding farms were taught by one teacher.
 
Around 1900, a larger frame building was erected. By 1930 more room was needed, so a brick addition was constructed. A short time later, fire struck and building was lost. The new school, which included a library and gymnasium, was called Cherry Hills School. There were about 40 students spread over nine grades.
 
When the School District decided to consolidate Cherry Hills and Village Heights Elementary Schools, a new building was erected on the site and given the name of Cherry Hills Village Elementary School. The new school opened in September 1984.

name: BVSD RYAN ELEMENTARY SAC
details:
School Profile Ryan Elementary STEAM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Arts, and Mathematics) School is a wonderful learning community where students, staff, and families authentically partner to make each day a powerful learning experience for our children. In addition to delivering the BVSD standards-based Guaranteed and Viable Curriculum, Ryan Elementary STEAM school focuses on developing the whole child with experiential learning activities in the areas of Science, Technology, Engineering, Arts, and Mathematics.

Ryan is the only BVSD elementary school with interactive white boards, document cameras, and 3-D projectors in every classroom, and is currently piloting the use of I-Pads and I-Pods to enhance student learning in the areas of science and literacy. We strongly believe partnerships nurture excellence and therefore we embrace partnerships with the University of Colorado at Boulder, Thorne Ecological Institute, and Impact on Education to name a few. We offer a wide variety of after-school programming to extend the learning day and to support our focus. We also offer monthly learning symposiums to our students and the families who support them as a way to build community and shared learning for all.

name: COTTONWOOD PLAINS B.A.S.E.
details:
Our Before and After School Programs are activity based and support classroom learning, providing help with homework, snacks, arts & crafts, sports, science & music activities. Through these programs children develop academic, socialization, arts, athletic, and communication skills which instill them with the confidence and ability to succeed in their school and community.

Programs are tailored to meet each school’s unique requests, and to identify and respond to each child’s needs. A broad range of experience, talent, and skills allow our diverse staff to build programs in collaboration with school staff that respond to changing demo-graphics, backgrounds, and academic levels.

Summer Camp is an “all about fun” program that also focuses on preventing “summer slide” (a loss of previous year’s learning) and returning children to the classroom in the fall at their grade level and ready to learn. The program offers a “green” environment with children learning sustainable living practices such as gardening, composting, and recycling. Partial and full Scholarships make these experiences available to children who would not otherwise have them.

School Out Days (SOD) offers special activities on those days when school is not in session such as teacher conference days, in-service days, holiday breaks, and spring break. SOD’s are held at one or two school sites accessible to all students. During this time, the children focus on special themes such as arts, sciences, sports, music, and drama. They also take field trips and periodically hear speakers and instructors regarding particular topics of interest.

details:
The Durango 4-C Council, Inc. is a private non-profit 501(c)3 corporation whose “purposes and objectives are to serve as the Governing Board of the Tri-County Head Start/ Early Childhood Programs and to promote and coordinate quality child care and family services in the Southwest Colorado area.”

     The Durango 4-C Councils (Community Coordinated Child Care) were established in the 1960s under a federal initiative to improve child care throughout the United States. The first Head Start program in Durango was under the 4-C Council.

     The Durango 4-C Council was incorporated as a non-profit in 1972, and became the governing board for the Tri-County Head Start program serving low-income at-risk children in Archuleta, La Plata, and Montezuma counties.

    Today the Durango 4-C Council is promoting quality child care services throughout Southwest Colorado through the Early Childhood Professional Development Project, Southwest Office of Resource & Referral, Qualistar partnership, Expanding Quality Infant Toddler Training, and early childhood systems development through the Early Childhood Council of La Plata County.

    The Board of Directors of the Durango 4-C Council consists of 15 members representing three sectors of the community: Agency representatives, Private Sector representatives, and Parent representatives. The activities of the council are carried out under the supervision of the Executive Director.

Students work in a carefully prepared environment that invites curiosity and promotes investigation and exploration. Students are encouraged to collaborate in their learning during work cycles. Lessons are presented to individual students or in small groups.  Welby supports the Primary Program, which provides a fourth year of school for children in kindergarten through second grade who need more time to develop essential reading skills, such as early reading and vocabulary development.

name: BUENA VISTA ELEMENTARY SCHOOL
details:
Buena Vista Montessori Philosophy Statement
    Students learn at all grade levels through teacher-led and student-initiated projects.  Independent study and group projects allow students to learn state standards through in-depth investigations into areas of personal interest to the student through which they become independent and self motivated learners.  Driven by constructivist pedagogy, teachers facilitate the work of students as producers and learners and students further their own learning through acting as role models and advisors to other students, and by completing projects and presenting them as part of the learning environment.
    Students work with their teacher to develop a weekly work plan known in traditional teaching circles as a personal learning plan (PLP) so that they know and can reach academic standards and personal growth.  This practice allows students to be in control of their own learning path, chart their own progress, recognize areas of strength and weakness, and actively reflect on their own learning.  The work plan enables teachers and students to track their own growth and progression towards mastery.
    Our students work towards personal goals, not simply getting exposure, but diving deeply into topics and projects.  The students’ work is profoundly relevant to each student through the personalized learning plans, student-generated projects, and consistent work with families and the local community. The small learning environment becomes a true community in which respect for and connection with each other is paramount.  Restorative justice, “Love and Logic”, class and school gatherings are central components to creating this powerful place of lifelong learning.
    Adapted in part from the pedagogical framework of High Desert Montessori School, the work of Maria Montessori and the vision of Buena Vista Montessori School.

name: MY SCHOOL PRESCHOOL
details:
Welcome to My School Preschool’s website. We hope that you find it a great introduction to our school. Like our school, we want this site to be a place for you to discover things about My School Preschool (MSP) that excite you and make you want to know more. 

There is a page that highlights our wonderful teachers, who take professional and personal pride in building strong relationships with their students and their student’s families. There is a page dedicated to our unique program that merges best practices and our students' desire to learn with amazing results. There are also pages that are more nuts and bolts in nature: the admissions process, tuition structure, class schedule and programs, and how to contact us.

This website also conveys the love we have for children, the uniqueness they bring to our school, and how everyone who walks through our doors teaches respect and care for others by modeling those attributes. When you are finished browsing our site, please call the school and arrange a time to come and experience our dynamic school first hand. 

Let us share what researchers have found: young children learn best through their five senses. While visiting the school your senses will be engaged in a way that they cannot be by web page alone. We invite you to come and let your eyes see the Taj Mahal being built in the block area and children delivering letters they wrote to their friends, while dressed in postmaster uniforms. Let your ears hear the giggles of four year-olds laughing at made-up jokes, two and a half and three year-olds singing, and five year-olds trying to make a friend feel better by talking with them. Come and feel rice fall through your fingers at a sensory table, feel the coolness of finger paint on your hands, and feel the love from a teacher to a child. You might be able to smell scented play dough and the chill on children returning from our amazing outdoor playground. If you time your visit just right, you may be able to share a snack or a birthday celebration with a class, and you will get to go home with a taste of My School Preschool. 

Since 1971 My School Preschool has been educating young children in the Villages. Come and see if My School Preschool’s community is the place for your child to take his or her first step on a life long journey of learning.

name: FOOTHILLS OUTDOOR EXPERIENTAL CAMP
details:
Foothills Park & Recreation District was established on December 31, 1959 as South Jeffco Metropolitan Recreation and Park District and consisted of one park site. The District was renamed Foothills in 1970 and currently maintains the Ridge Recreation Center, Edge Ice Arena, Lilley Gulch Recreation Center, Peak Community and Wellness Center, four outdoor swimming pools, Indoor Sports Arena, Foothills Golf Course complex, Meadows Golf Course, and 71 park sites totaling more than 2,600 acres and including three regional parks,44 neighborhood and community parks and 24 greenbelts. In addition Foothills manages six regional trail corridors for public use, which, combined with park trails, total 38.3 miles.

The District boundaries encompass about 28 square miles and serves a population of approximately 90,000 residents. Foothills offers over 4,000 classes and programs which include a wide variety of programs for all ages.

The red rocks of the hogback provide a spectacularly beautiful backdrop for our geographical boundaries, which generally are Hampden Avenue on the north, Sheridan Boulevard on the east and C-470 on the south and west. Other areas we serve that fall just outside the complex street boundaries are Sixth Avenue West, Mesa View Estates, Bear Creek subdivision and Lochwood subdivision. All areas served by Foothills Park & Recreation District are within unincorporated Jefferson County.

details:
Our Before and After School Programs are activity based and support classroom learning, providing help with homework, snacks, arts & crafts, sports, science & music activities. Through these programs children develop academic, socialization, arts, athletic, and communication skills which instill them with the confidence and ability to succeed in their school and community.

Programs are tailored to meet each school’s unique requests, and to identify and respond to each child’s needs. A broad range of experience, talent, and skills allow our diverse staff to build programs in collaboration with school staff that respond to changing demo-graphics, backgrounds, and academic levels.

Summer Camp is an “all about fun” program that also focuses on preventing “summer slide” (a loss of previous year’s learning) and returning children to the classroom in the fall at their grade level and ready to learn. The program offers a “green” environment with children learning sustainable living practices such as gardening, composting, and recycling. Partial and full Scholarships make these experiences available to children who would not otherwise have them.

School Out Days (SOD) offers special activities on those days when school is not in session such as teacher conference days, in-service days, holiday breaks, and spring break. SOD’s are held at one or two school sites accessible to all students. During this time, the children focus on special themes such as arts, sciences, sports, music, and drama. They also take field trips and periodically hear speakers and instructors regarding particular topics of interest.

details:
Our motto at Red Hawk Ridge Elementary is "Learning For All ­Whatever It Takes," and you will see this message as you walk into our front hallway. This is a reminder that your student is attending a school with high and rigorous academic expectations for all. Our teachers and staff work hard to provide a balanced curriculum exceeding district and state content standards in a safe, caring and inclusive community.
 
The students at Red Hawk Ridge have many opportunities outside of the classroom to enhance their elementary experience. Art, music, physical education, drama, choir, technology and various clubs are some of the classes that are offered during and before school.
 
Part of the Red Hawk Ridge Elementary School's Mission focuses on the building of a community. We believe in the shared dedication and responsibility of the child, family, school and community as partners in meeting challenges and celebrating success. As a community, we will empower all students to achieve academic excellence.
 
Red Hawk Ridge is a 4-track, year-round school, which means we have children attending school every month of the year. About three-quarters of our student body is in attendance at any one time. Students attend the same number of days of school, but the schedule for time off varies by track. We serve approximately 700 students in grades kindergarten through fifth grade.
The staff at Red Hawk Ridge thanks you for your support in building a strong home/school relationship.

name: ST. THOMAS MORE PARISH SCHOOL
details:
STM Catholic is a parochial school, deeply rooted in the Gospel of Jesus Christ and the teaching of the Catholic Church. In the great tradition of Catholic education, we remain devoted to the development of the whole person in each of our students.

The School strives to nurture in its students, an awareness and love of God and a sense of moral responsibility. We believe that the spiritual growth of our students gives meaning to their intellectual and physical pursuits. We hold that it is only in the context of valuing their relationship with God, discovering their individual gifts and talents, and accepting their responsibilities toward self and community, that they can pursue an education that prepares them to lead fulfilling lives.

STM Catholic encourages each of its students to actively seek knowledge and understanding in pursuit of the truth. The objective of the School's rigorous academic program is to develop in each student the skills of examination and expression; to provide a solid foundation in the fundamental fields of human knowledge; to cultivate an ability to think critically, creatively, and independently; and to inspire intellectual curiosity and a passion for learning.

Also integral to the STM Catholic experience, our physical education and athletic programs serve to instill certain qualities of character; to develop strength of body and alertness of mind; and to illuminate the value of life-long fitness and health. Emphasizing self-discipline, teamwork, perseverance, sportsmanship, and striving toward a goal, the physical dimension of an STM Catholic education provides important lessons for life's challenges.
- See more at: http://stmcatholic.org/about-us/mission-philosophy#sthash.hc43maiK.dpuf

details:
Helping children achieve academic and personal excellence through individualized education.

Founded in 1976, Rivendell School is the oldest nonprofit secular private school in Fort Collins. Thanks to the vision and hard work of our state-licensed teachers and involved parents, we have proudly helped hundreds of children grow into well-educated, imaginative, caring, and responsible citizens.

Rivendell School’s individualized approach to education—a proven method for increasing subject mastery—focuses on the progress of each child rather than on the class average. Each student is constantly evaluated, challenged, and encouraged to perform to his or her full potential. Engaging every individual in the learning process produces the best results for each student.

name: ADAMS 12 FIVE STAR / ARAPAHOE RIDGE BASE
details:
Our Before and After School Programs are activity based and support classroom learning, providing help with homework, snacks, arts & crafts, sports, science & music activities. Through these programs children develop academic, socialization, arts, athletic, and communication skills which instill them with the confidence and ability to succeed in their school and community.

Programs are tailored to meet each school’s unique requests, and to identify and respond to each child’s needs. A broad range of experience, talent, and skills allow our diverse staff to build programs in collaboration with school staff that respond to changing demo-graphics, backgrounds, and academic levels.

Summer Camp is an “all about fun” program that also focuses on preventing “summer slide” (a loss of previous year’s learning) and returning children to the classroom in the fall at their grade level and ready to learn. The program offers a “green” environment with children learning sustainable living practices such as gardening, composting, and recycling. Partial and full Scholarships make these experiences available to children who would not otherwise have them.

School Out Days (SOD) offers special activities on those days when school is not in session such as teacher conference days, in-service days, holiday breaks, and spring break. SOD’s are held at one or two school sites accessible to all students. During this time, the children focus on special themes such as arts, sciences, sports, music, and drama. They also take field trips and periodically hear speakers and instructors regarding particular topics of interest.

name: POLTON ECS PROGAMS
details:
At Polton we strive to create an equitable, student-centered environment, by demonstrating Polton P.R.I.D.E. It is through demonstrating this vision that we uphold our mission, “As a designated school of Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math (S.T.E.M.), Polton Community Elementary School is dedicated to equitable educating and preparing all students for success in the 21st century. At Polton our work is guided by: 

P – Proud – Ensuring that students, staff and community take ownership in learning and successes through shared partnerships. 

R – Respectful – Appreciating differences through our Caring Community while developing responsible risk-takers. 

I – Intelligent – Enhancing college preparedness and cooperative learning through S.T.E.M., Literacy, Social Studies and the Arts. 

D – Determined – Expecting academic rigor through problem solving and collaboration, while eliminating all achievement gaps. 

​​E – Excellent – Fostering life-long learners through stakeholder (students, staff, community, district) ownership of data and the development of leadership skills.

name: BVSD ELDORADO K8 SAC
details:
Eldorado K-8 is a community centerpiece where all minds are opened to lifelong learning and achievement through innovative and challenging educational experiences.

Eldorado K-8...
 Believes in high expectations and success for all students. We will provide learning experiences to meet the unique and diverse needs and strengths of each learner so that each child achieves his/her "personal best".
 Provides a well-balanced and challenging curriculum that supports the interests of students and reflects our commitment to the highest academic standards.
 Provides a safe physical, social, and emotional environment in which all members of the school community feel cared for and connected:

        Every child "belongs" and is valued. Our students' voices are encouraged through meaningful democratic participation. We encourage risk-taking, problem solving, and critical thinking.
        School-wide discipline policies are clearly articulated and consistently enforced. Whenever possible, they will be stated positively and supported by natural consequences.
        Our building is warm, open, and welcoming to our families and the community. It is respected and cared for by all.
        Our diversity is one of our greatest strengths. We will treat all people with respect and understanding. Staff and students will reflect honor to themselves, to their families, and to their community.
        Is committed to creating a unified and cohesive learning community through cross grade level collaboration and K-12 articulation.
        Is committed to creating powerful partnerships in learning with: our students, teachers, and staff; our families; our community (city and business); and our world.
        Is committed to ongoing professional development for staff to ensure that our students are provided the very best educational experience.
        Celebrates successes, learns quickly from mistakes, dares to take risks, and collaborates whenever possible.

name: GREENLEE METRO EXTENDED DAY
details:
Denver Public Schools Mission

“…to provide all students the opportunity to achieve the knowledge and skills necessary to become contributing citizens in our diverse society.”

Widely recognized today as one of the best urban school systems in the country, Denver Public Schools serves the residents of the City and County of Denver, Colorado.

While its roots can be traced to 1859, when the city was founded, the district was officially created in 1902 when voters approved a constitutional amendment that created the City and County of Denver. The same constitutional amendment consolidated five school districts into today’s School District No. 1.

We are committed to Peakview being a place where:
    we will develop and display traits of compassion, respect, and cooperation
    we will demonstrate a sense of purpose that reflects a commitment to discovery, productivity and initiative
    we will encourage and exhibit a spirit of inventiveness, curiosity, and ingenuity
    we will build a solid foundation of academic concepts and skills, combined with the attitudes needed to use them
    we will identify and nurture our personal capacities to solve problems, evaluate choices, make decisions, and take risks
    we will understand and value the importance of our connection to the community and the world beyond

name: SUNRISE ENTERPRISE
details:
Our Philosophy
 Teachers and students at Sunrise work together in applying both traditional and innovative approaches to learning that build a strong academic foundation and encourage the spirit of creativity, curiosity, and productivity. Expectations are high for all students. Through such practices as literature-based reading instruction, guided reading, a manipulative approach to math through the Everyday Math® series, writing using the Lucy Calkins Units of Study ® approach, application of the scientific method and multiple assessments, our students continue to grow and achieve.
 
Throughout the day the needs and unique learning styles of each individual student are taken into account as the curriculum is modified to challenge the highly motivated students, encourage the reluctant learner, and reach all students in between. At Sunrise, every student’s progress is important.

name: TRAILS WEST ADVENTURES
details: Trails West’s dedicated staff is a collaborative faculty who is committed to the districts mission of inspiring every child to think, to learn, to achieve, and to care.  Here at Trails West students, teachers, parents, and community members partner together to inspire lifelong learning.

name: FRONTIER ADVENTURE CLUB
details: Our mission is to provide a recreational childcare environment, encompassing all the needs areas (social, emotional, physical, and cognitive) during “out of school time” for elementary school age children and day time hours for Preschool age.  The club atmosphere will bring an open attitude of community with a safe, healthy, nurturing program. Children can thrive through developmentally appropriate and child directed challenges that are fun and unique to each individual.

name: G K S GYMNASTICS KIDS CLUB
S.O.T.H. CHRISTIAN PRESCHOOL
details:
Welcome to Shepherd of the Hills Christian Preschool.  Upon entering the Shepherd campus, you and your child will be greeted by devoted teaching professionals eagerly waiting to partner with you for your child’s growth, development and education.

Our large and vibrant classrooms are rich with materials and resources waiting for your child to explore.  Low student to teacher ratios allow our teachers to nurture the God-given potential of every child.

Shepherd of the Hills Christian Preschool offers a comprehensive educational program with flexible schedule options (part and full-time options) that meet the unique needs of families.

Our curriculum framework aligns with the Colorado Common Core Standards, and we use authentic assessment to inform educational planning and practice.  Take a moment to schedule a visit and I am sure that you will agree Shepherd of the Hills Christian Preschool is a place where your child can “Learn and Grow in God’s Love.”

name: HOMESTEAD SCHOOL AGE CHILDCARE PROGRAM
details:
The staff of Homestead Elementary School believes in inspiring all students to think, to learn, to achieve and to care. We work collaboratively with one another to provide students a well-balanced education. Homestead provides a nurturing environment where students feel respected, valued and safe. We are committed to using varied instructional strategies focused on helping all students succeed.

These strategies are based on best practice and include direct instruction to enhance skill attainment, project opportunities for skill application and homework to reinforce classroom learning.

name: SAGEBRUSH DAYCARE
details:
Welcome to Sagebrush where we embrace moments and opportunities, "To inspire every student to think, to learn, to achieve, to care."  We take pride in our quest for excellence and commit our best efforts to ensure your child receives a high quality education.

Our positive relationship with your child is a priority.  We foster that relationship by valuing each child's unique strengths and contributions.  We hold high expectations and build confidence as we encourage students to reach high and to think positively.  Sagebrush provides academic excellence with a rigorous curriculum and instruction that differentiates to meet the potential of the individual child.  We develop academic achievement through the use of research based programs and practices.

We believe in the power of parent partnerships that support academic growth and achievement.  We know what a positive difference a strong home-school connection makes and expect parents to support school efforts at home.       Additionally, parent involvement is evident in school activities and we welcome your contributions.  We care about your child and pledge our best in providing him/her an education of excellence!
- See more at:

name: BEAVER CREEK DAY CAMP
details: Beaver Creek Kids Day Camp is your best option for summer fun in the Vail Valley! Your kids will have a blast and enhance those creative brains as they play in the beautiful Colorado Mountains. We have three separate camps that go out every day. Discovery Camp is for ages 5-7, Adventure Camp is for ages 8-13 and Five Star Camp is for all ages 5-13 allowing families to stay together. Rock Climbing, Backcountry Jeep Tours, Horseback Riding, Pontoon Boating, Alpine Slide and visits to the Matawin Tipi Village are just some of the amazing activities your child will do while here at camp. For our destination guest’s lunch and two healthy hearty snacks are provided. For our local guests we provide two snacks and you can purchase lunch for $10 or bring a sack lunch from home.

name: BRIARGATE PRESCHOOL
details: "Our mission at D20 Preschools is to plant the seeds of success in young children by providing self-initiated, inquiry-based, active education through play based instruction. The children learn how to work with others and become enthusiastic intentional learners through a child centered, developmentally appropriate based curriculum".

name: DPS ECE BARNEY FORD ELEMENTARY
details: The philosophy of the Early Education Department is to create an integrated and comprehensive system of diverse, high quality early childhood education and care services. This system of services will enhance the development of young children so they succeed throughout their academic career; support families in their role as nurturers and first teachers; and meet the needs and financial abilities of Denver’s working parents.

name: BETTY ADAMS PRESCHOOL
details: Campbell Elementary School is committed to creating an environment that promotes student achievement and success by addressing individual student needs, integrating technology, holding high expectations for all students, promoting safety throughout the school, and encouraging parent-community participation. Campbell is a school that has a sense of community with a family centered atmosphere. Our school serves 340 students in K through 6th grades. We are proud of our wide variety of extra-curricular activities which include science lab, science fair, cross country, student council, choir, lego club, jump rope club and dance.

name: EARLY CHILDHOOD CENTER AT GREGORY HILLS
PINNACLE CHARTER SCHOOL B.A.S.E. PROGRAM
details:
Our Before and After School Programs are activity based and support classroom learning, providing help with homework, snacks, arts & crafts, sports, science & music activities. Through these programs children develop academic, socialization, arts, athletic, and communication skills which instill them with the confidence and ability to succeed in their school and community.

Programs are tailored to meet each school’s unique requests, and to identify and respond to each child’s needs. A broad range of experience, talent, and skills allow our diverse staff to build programs in collaboration with school staff that respond to changing demo-graphics, backgrounds, and academic levels.

Summer Camp is an “all about fun” program that also focuses on preventing “summer slide” (a loss of previous year’s learning) and returning children to the classroom in the fall at their grade level and ready to learn. The program offers a “green” environment with children learning sustainable living practices such as gardening, composting, and recycling. Partial and full Scholarships make these experiences available to children who would not otherwise have them.

School Out Days (SOD) offers special activities on those days when school is not in session such as teacher conference days, in-service days, holiday breaks, and spring break. SOD’s are held at one or two school sites accessible to all students. During this time, the children focus on special themes such as arts, sciences, sports, music, and drama. They also take field trips and periodically hear speakers and instructors regarding particular topics of interest.

name: STELLAR ELEMENTARY BASE PROGRAM
details:
Stellar Elementary empowers children to own a dream and reach their star potential. Stellar Stars are grown through a rigorous instruction that meets every child where they are and then motivates them to achieve the highest expectations. At Stellar, we use various methodologies to foster mastery of state educational standards. The Kagan instructional approach offers one method to facilitate cooperative learning. All learners are accountable for participation and critical thinking, while focusing on classroom and team building techniques.

The Stellar campus is working toward brain-based, conceptually integrated instruction and we meet each week in our professional learning communities to collaborate, plan, address student needs and grow as educators. Stellar shares the collective belief with parents that it is our passion to inspire our students by nurturing independence and encouraging risk taking in a supportive, positive environment. Personal accountability is one part of the dynamic of seizing a dream and setting smart goals that build toward success. We encourage students to set goals that reflect their passions and then review and revise based on personal growth.

We value parents as learning partners and have a variety of options for parent volunteer involvement, including targeted reading time for direct student mentoring as well as various support opportunities.

name: ARROWHEAD ECS PROGRAM
details: Arrowhead Elementary is a K-5 elementary school of 630 students. Our mission at Arrowhead Elementary is to provide daily rigorous academic instruction within a school climate that is physically and emotionally safe for every child, creating a learning environment where each child is able to achieve his or her full potential. We consider our parent community as partners in our mission to provide focused academic instruction each day.  As a PBS school community, we follow our ‘3 Bees’, to be safe, be respectful, and be responsible, in order to provide an effective learning atmosphere.  Our Excellence and Equity Goals each year align with our mission of supporting each student in reaching his or her full academic and social potential while attending Arrowhead.  We are most proud of our hard-working and focused students, our dedicated and highly qualified teachers, and our supportive parent community.  For information on more current school topics, please see The Thunderbird Times link on our website. - See more at: http://arrowhead.cherrycreekschools.org/Pages/PrincipalsMessage.aspx#sthash.cdtRJRgm.dpuf

name: ANTELOPE RIDGE EXPLORERS
details:
Welcome to Antelope Ridge Elementary School where every day is a great day to be an Antelope.  I am honored to be the principal of such an amazing school with outstanding staff, students and parents. 
 
You will find our staff is dedicated, hardworking, and child-focused.  They inspire students to think, to learn, to achieve, and to care in many different ways.  Through rigorous instruction based upon best practices, our staff is able to meet the needs of each individual child and allow them to reach their full potential.
 
Our students are ready and eager to learn each and every day.  They are diligent in their studies and thrive in an environment of safety, respect, and high expectations.  They are kind and respectful to each other and go out of their way to demonstrate our school-wide expectations of Honor, Effort, Responsibility and Dedication.  
 
The parents of Antelope Ridge have many opportunities to become involved.  Through PTCO (Parent, Teacher, Community Organization), PASS (Partnership for Academically Successful Students), Accountability Committee or through volunteering, you are sure to find your niche as a parent.

name: CAMP BELLEVIEW
details:
Welcome to Belle view Elementary School.  We are proud of our school, staff, students, and community who are all committed to our District’s Mission: “ To inspire every child  to think, to learn, to achieve, to care.”

Belleview Elementary School is a building that is comprised of grades K-5.  We provide opportunities in the areas of: intervention, enrichment, character education, Specials (Music, Art, PE, Technology, Media), and technology integration.  Our school values traditional, yet rigorous opportunities in learning.  Our teachers use exemplary instructional strategies that are flexible to the needs of our student population, and utilize multiple data points in planning for instruction.    We cherish the importance of home-school partnerships, and we are committed to the hearts and minds of every child.  We are proud to share we are a John Irwin School of Excellence and recipient of the Governor’s Distinguished Growth Award.  These accomplishments are possible due to the high level of partnerships with our staff and community (Please visit www.schoolview.org to find out more information on our school achievement.).

Belleview’s dedicated staff is a collaborative faculty whose top priority is the growth and development of the whole child.  In addition to academics, we host annual school events including  a school-wide Shakespeare production, opportunities for students’ art to be showcased in the local community, various musical performances, and an intermediate grade ballroom dancing competition, to name a few.  As a wellness school, we have adopted the recess-before-lunch model, and host many opportunities for students to foster their wellness, such as field day, running club, physical education courses, and much more (For more information on wellness, please visit our district website.).

Parental involvement is at the heart of student success at Belleview.  We are extremely fortunate to have an abundance of parent leadership and volunteers who enrich our school with their time, heart, and talent.  The highly supportive Parent Teacher Community Organization (PTCO) is a vital part of our school environment.  Our PTCO are parent leaders who host school-wide events for our students and help in raising funds for our school, which are utilized to directly benefit students and classrooms.  In fact, through fundraising efforts and the support of our community, our PTCO provided state-of-the-art technological resources such as: document cameras, printer stations, SMARTBoards, a new computer lab, and a two carts of laptops for our classrooms. We are extremely grateful for the wonderful resources provided by our community.   In our dedication to 21st –century learning, we will continue to maximize our efforts in technology integration into the classroom environment.   

We are so glad you are a part of the Belleview family.  Please do not hesitate to contact me if you should have any questions, comments or concerns.  The following quote by Mattie Stepanek  speaks true to our school community, “Unity is strength.  Where there is teamwork, wonderful things can be achieved.”  We look forward to partnering with you in your child(ren’s) success!

name: MISSION VIEJO EXTENDED CHILD SERVICES
details: As I begin my fifth year as the principal at Mission Viejo, I want to express my appreciation to each and every one of you for all the things you've done to make my first four years so memorable.  Though the primary role of schools is educate children, I have learned so much from being a part of this community.  Among the things I’ve learned is how kind and hardworking every teacher, parent and student is.  Seeing you all work hard inspires me to work hard as well.  Please know that I am committed to the continuous improvement of our school.  I want to ensure that our students have the best academic and social environment from the time they step into the building until the time they leave. - See more at: http://missionviejo.cherrycreekschools.org/Pages/PrincipalsMessage.aspx#sthash.d2ivNiGu.dpuf

name: RED HAWK RIDGE ECS PROGRAM
details:
Our motto at Red Hawk Ridge Elementary is "Learning For All ­Whatever It Takes," and you will see this message as you walk into our front hallway. This is a reminder that your student is attending a school with high and rigorous academic expectations for all. Our teachers and staff work hard to provide a balanced curriculum exceeding district and state content standards in a safe, caring and inclusive community.
 
The students at Red Hawk Ridge have many opportunities outside of the classroom to enhance their elementary experience. Art, music, physical education, drama, choir, technology and various clubs are some of the classes that are offered during and before school.
 
Part of the Red Hawk Ridge Elementary School's Mission focuses on the building of a community. We believe in the shared dedication and responsibility of the child, family, school and community as partners in meeting challenges and celebrating success. As a community, we will empower all students to achieve academic excellence.
 
Red Hawk Ridge is a 4-track, year-round school, which means we have children attending school every month of the year. About three-quarters of our student body is in attendance at any one time. Students attend the same number of days of school, but the schedule for time off varies by track. We serve approximately 700 students in grades kindergarten through fifth grade.
The staff at Red Hawk Ridge thanks you for your support in building a strong home/school relationship.

name: WILLOW CREEK CARES FOR KIDS
details: Willow Creek Elementary School is the sum of many factors equaling the perfect equation. The mission of Cherry Creek Schools, and thus of Willow Creek, is "To inspire every student to think, to learn, to achieve, and to care." By honoring the core values listed below, Willow Creek excels with an amazing pool of students, teachers, administrators, staff members, parents, and community supporters.

name: MERIDIAN BASE PROGRAM
details:
Our Before and After School Programs are activity based and support classroom learning, providing help with homework, snacks, arts & crafts, sports, science & music activities. Through these programs children develop academic, socialization, arts, athletic, and communication skills which instill them with the confidence and ability to succeed in their school and community.

Programs are tailored to meet each school’s unique requests, and to identify and respond to each child’s needs. A broad range of experience, talent, and skills allow our diverse staff to build programs in collaboration with school staff that respond to changing demo-graphics, backgrounds, and academic levels.

Summer Camp is an “all about fun” program that also focuses on preventing “summer slide” (a loss of previous year’s learning) and returning children to the classroom in the fall at their grade level and ready to learn. The program offers a “green” environment with children learning sustainable living practices such as gardening, composting, and recycling. Partial and full Scholarships make these experiences available to children who would not otherwise have them.

School Out Days (SOD) offers special activities on those days when school is not in session such as teacher conference days, in-service days, holiday breaks, and spring break. SOD’s are held at one or two school sites accessible to all students. During this time, the children focus on special themes such as arts, sciences, sports, music, and drama. They also take field trips and periodically hear speakers and instructors regarding particular topics of interest.

name: MONTESSORI PEAKS ACADEMY
details: Montessori Peaks Academy is a Colorado public charter school and tuition-based preschool located in Littleton, Colorado in the Jefferson County school district. MPA provides programs for children from preschool age 3 through sixth grade. To meet the needs of our families, we offer before- and after-school childcare and enrichment activities. We also offer a special Friday program for home schooled children which includes art, music and P.E. as well as classroom activities.

name: CITY OF WESTMINSTER / YOUTH / TEEN CAMPS
MOUNTAIN CENTER DAY CAMP
details: For over 35 years, Mountain Kids has been providing children quality instruction.  We have programs to fit any skill level from beginning dance classes to advanced competitive gymnastics teams and performance dance companies. Our dancers have performed at Walt Disney World in Orlando, FL, and our gymnastics teams have produced numerous regional, state, and national qualifiers and champions. Choose either our Mountain Kids Fort Collins or Mountain Kids Louisville location to become a member of the Mountain Kids family.

name: PARK HILL UNTD MTHDST CHILDRENS CTR
details:
The Children’s Center at the Park Hill United Methodist Church (PHUMC) is a treasured community institution. Our center strives to provide high quality services to local families in need of preschool and childcare options.

We were established in 1979 by the Park Hill United Methodist Church to fill a growing need in the area for half day, full-day and after school care options.  Our non-profit organization was created as an outreach program, with a non-denominational, developmentally appropriate curriculum and philosophy. Children of all religious and cultural backgrounds are welcome.

For more than 30 years, the Children’s Center has served young families in our community by  providing options that support the rich tradition of diversity and the values of our neighborhood.

We understand that choosing a caregiver for your child(ren) is an enormous decision for families.  To that end, we are available for touring Monday – Friday between 10am and 6pm.  Walk-ins are welcome, or if you prefer, you can call to set up an appointment.  It is our goal to answer all  questions and provide a clear understanding of our program. Additionally, we have a wide  assortment of informational documents available to begin the wait list and/or enrollment process.

Parents, children, friends and extended family are all welcome to visit our facility and spend as much time as desired gathering information, observing and playing with our children and staff.

name: HEAD START COLORADO PRESCHOOL PROJECT
details: Yuma County Head Start is a center based program serving 34 families in Yuma County. We have two centers, one located in Wray, Colorado and the other in Yuma, Colorado.  The communities are approximately 30 miles apart. The grantee for our program is the Wray School District RD-2. Our management staff includes the RD-2 Superintendent as our Executive Director, a Head Start Director, Family Services Coordinator and Education Coordinator.  We employ a teacher, assistant teacher, and classroom aide in each center.  Our food and transportation services are provided through the respective school districts.

name: ENGLEWOOD SCHOOLS ECE
details:
The Englewood School District is proud to offer the Englewood Early Childhood Education Program at Maddox to families in the community. Our mission is to help children develop a positive attitude toward learning and to support children’s social and educational development. We provide integrated services that build a foundation for lifelong learning and support the role of parents as partners in their child’s educational development.
 
Funded preschool is available for children between the ages of 3 and 5 years old who meet eligibility requirements through the Colorado Preschool Program, Head Start or Special Education and provides a comprehensive system of services which address child, family and community needs. Preschool is also available for children on a tuition basis.

name: SHERIDAN PRESCHOOL
details: The Sheridan Early Childhood Center is devoted to understanding the needs of young children and their families in our community. We create partnerships with families to enhance child and family development. We respond to identified needs by offering choices related to quality education, healthcare services, family involvement, and social services in a safe and supportive environment.

name: UPPER ARKANSA AREA COUNCIL OF GOVERNMENTS HEA
DAKOTA VALLEY ELEMENTARY SCHOOL
details:
Welcome to Dakota Valley Elementary! I am honored to be a principal of a school where a genuine love for children, high expectations and character building are a priority. The staff at Dakota Valley Elementary is committed to helping each child reach his or her potential academically, socially and behaviorally.
 
You will find Dakota Valley Elementary School to be a very safe, welcoming and student-centered environment where students can grow and learn. I am fortunate to have a staff that values this philosophy while also setting very high standards for student learning. We are a preschool through 5th grade building with more than 800 students. Though we are a large school, we have maintained a family-like atmosphere with our four track calendar.
 
We recognize that parents are our students’ first and best teachers. We encourage our parents to be active partners in the school, ensuring the success of their children. We have a very active Parent Teacher Organization, many opportunities to volunteer in the school and classrooms, and a strong PASS (Partnership for Academically Successful Students) committee. All provide many, many opportunities to get involved. Additionally, we typically have over 90% attendance at Parent-Teacher conferences illustrating that parents are also committed to helping us achieve our mission of student success.
 
I would like to encourage you to explore our website to learn more about our curriculum, staff, programs, activities and classrooms. We are extremely proud of the accomplishments of our students and staff and we hope you enjoy Dakota Valley Elementary School.

name: HIGHLANDS RANCH COMM ASSOC DAY CAMP
JOHNSON B.A.S.E. CAMP
details:
Our Before and After School Programs are activity based and support classroom learning, providing help with homework, snacks, arts & crafts, sports, science & music activities. Through these programs children develop academic, socialization, arts, athletic, and communication skills which instill them with the confidence and ability to succeed in their school and community.

Programs are tailored to meet each school’s unique requests, and to identify and respond to each child’s needs. A broad range of experience, talent, and skills allow our diverse staff to build programs in collaboration with school staff that respond to changing demo-graphics, backgrounds, and academic levels.

Summer Camp is an “all about fun” program that also focuses on preventing “summer slide” (a loss of previous year’s learning) and returning children to the classroom in the fall at their grade level and ready to learn. The program offers a “green” environment with children learning sustainable living practices such as gardening, composting, and recycling. Partial and full Scholarships make these experiences available to children who would not otherwise have them.

School Out Days (SOD) offers special activities on those days when school is not in session such as teacher conference days, in-service days, holiday breaks, and spring break. SOD’s are held at one or two school sites accessible to all students. During this time, the children focus on special themes such as arts, sciences, sports, music, and drama. They also take field trips and periodically hear speakers and instructors regarding particular topics of interest.

name: DREAM BIG DAY CAMP
details:
Whether or not your child wants to be a star, we're here to encourage children to be who they are!

Dream Big began in January 2006 with one class of four students (see Lisa Lang's staff profile picture).  It was a small class with big dreams!  Eight and a half years later, we have now grown to offer over 60 classes in and around the Chicagoland area, serving over 500 students weekly.  We currently offer our classes in Andersonville and Lakeview as well as in numerous schools including Bell, Bernard Zell Anshe Emet Day School, Boone, CICS-Irving Park, Hawthorne, Howe School of Excellence, Montessori Academy of Chicago, Newberry, Peirce, Pritzker, Solomon Schechter, St. Stanislaus-Kostka, Suder Montessori, Wildwood and Willa Cather (Super 7 Girls). We also partner with JCC Apachi Northside, Source 4 Chicago and various other non-profits to fulfill our mission of accommodating ALL students. (If you have a financial need, please let us know how we can help. We will never turn anyone away based on their ability to pay.) We are proud to announce additional programming for students in Saugatuck, Michigan and Phoenix, Arizona.

Dream Big Performing Arts Workshop offers a variety of drama classes to children ages 2-18.  Our classes are designed to foster creativity, self-expression and teamwork and, of course, to be a whole lot of fun!  All of our teachers have had years of experience in theatre as professional performers, directors, choreographers and/or writers and have a passion for teaching kids in the performing arts.  Some of our most popular classes include musical theatre, improvisation, story drama and, of course, our creatively themed 1-week drama camps!

name: PIONEER ATHLETIC SUPER SUMMER CAMP
details:
Pioneer Athletic Super Summer (P.A.S.S.) Camp is a DU summer tradition. Entering its 21st summer, P.A.S.S. Camp provides a weekly sport camp environment for campers ages 5 – 11.

P.A.S.S. Camp is a developmental sports camp focusing on sportsmanship, teamwork and the fundamentals of sports.

It also offers sport-specific training—what we call “sports majors”—that allows campers to gain experience in their sport of choice. At P.A.S.S. Camp, campers:
    Focus on a specific sports major for two hours each morning.
    Spend the rest of the day involved in a variety of sports activities.

We provide all required sports equipment.
P.A.S.S. Camp is also a licensed day care. It provides a 1:15 or better staff-to-camper ratio. All camp activities take place on the University of Denver campus.

name: YMCA OF BLDR VALLEY @ MANHATTAN MIDDLE SCH
details: The Y offers late start and after school programs for 6th-8th grade students. Caring, dedicated adults are there to listen to them and help them navigate the stresses, changes and choices that come with adolescence. Building relationships with these responsible adults and with other young people from different backgrounds helps give preteens the inner strength to avoid destructive behavior. Young people have more fun and learn more when they can take the lead in planning and directing their own programs, and the Y provides this opportunity.

name: DRY CREEK EXTENDED DAY PROGRAM
details:
We empower students to aspire toward academic excellence through scholarship and mentorship.
v Scholarship - Inspiring intellectual curiosity to promote lifelong learners.
v Mentorship - Building a spirit of community where students can achieve their potential.
v Aspiration - Emphasizing scholarship and mentorship for college preparation

name: YMCA OF METRO DENVER @  ASBURY ELEMENTARY
details:
Our daily curriculum makes us a unique child care provider, and sets us apart from others. We provide a mentoring relationship between your child and our caring staff that maximizes their personal empowerment, exploration and learning.

A safe setting, character values, positive role models and enrichment activities area all part of the Y child care experience.

name: KIDSTOWN HIGHLANDS RANCH
details: KidsTown provides licensed, clean and safe child care centers, with highly qualified staff, for the families of Colorado and Wyoming. Our centers are licensed to accept children between the ages of 12 months and 13 years.

name: BUFFALO RIDGE ELEMENTARY
details: The caring and dedicated Buffalo Ridge community collaboratively empowers innovative thinkers to meet the ever-changing challenges of a dynamic world through balance, problem-solving, and authentic learning.

name: EAGLE COUNTY SCHOOLS RED HILL  ELEMENTARY
COLORFUL BEGINNINGS  PRESCHOOL
details: Colorful Beginnings Preschool is dedicated to providing families with affordable childcare by trained staff, familiar with children's needs in a safe and nurturing Christian environment with Christian related materials appropriate to Child Development and Learning.

name: LITTLE MINDS LEARNING  CENTER-LITTLETON
details: Our facilities are part childcare, part child development, and part preschool and are certified for children between the ages of six weeks to six years old. We offer a premier child development experience that is both educational and affordable.

name: CHAMPIONS @ CROWN POINTE
details: Champions has a great solution for busy working families: activities that combine fun and learning, together with the safety and convenience of a high-quality program right inside your school. Champions offers a variety of group and individual activities designed to keep your child exploring and growing. From art, dramatic play, math and science to problem-solving, language, motor skills and more, we help your child continue learning and developing essential life skills – whether school is in session or not.

name: YPLC TEEN & FUN CAMP
details:
TeenCamp is designed just for 11-15 year olds.  NOBODY does anything like this.

We started Teen Camp in 1988 after realizing that 11 and 12 year olds had different interests than 8 year olds and deserved their own program!  Boy Scouts, Girl Scouts and the school district recognize the difference at age 11.  By this age, young teens talk, think, and act differently, and are ready for a program that respects and challenges them.  TeenCamp provides fun, safe, challenging, wholesome, age-appropriate activities for 11 – 15 year olds.

Integrity, Courtesy and Respect are the cornerstones of how TeenCampers treat each other and the community.  Each teen is expected to sign a Code of Conduct.  Most of our teens find long term friends who stay in touch throughout the year.  In addition, we take the opinions of the teens seriously and allow them to have input into the program whenever possible.   Within the limits of time, cost and appropriateness, teens can change the program.  No one else in our community offers a program for this age group and no one else could do it like this!

TeenCamp typically costs $50 per day or $225 for a full week.  There is an additional $10 if you choose to sign up for extended days when we go out for dinner as a group after our trips to Water World and Elitches and $45 in addition to daily charges for the two camping trips.  See the registration for a full explanation of charges.

name: JUNIPER RIDGE COMMUNITY  SCHOOL
details:
Our Vision at Juniper Ridge Community School is to awaken children to the wonder and joy of learning through nature combined with the living arts, academics, and the role these elements play in the development of the whole child. Our school nurtures creativity, individuality, and independent thinking so children have vast opportunity to pursue educational excellence, thus entering their community and the world with confidence, competence and compassion.

Juniper Ridge Community School is a multi-cultural K-7 charter school using an arts and nature-based curriculum rooted in the Waldorf tradition. A great body of research suggests the Waldorf approach of using art, nature, and a unique understanding of child development helps all children—regardless of aptitude or socio-economic status–reach remarkable academic and personal success. Waldorf-inspired graduates love to learn and continue to seek knowledge far beyond the last day of school, becoming highly valuable leaders and community members.

name: VISTA RIDGE ACADEMY
details: MISSION: To inspire learning for life in a Christ-centered environment by promoting creativity, excellence, integrity, respect and stewardship.
business hours:
Monday – Thursday
8:30 a.m. – 3:30 p.m.
Friday

name: ADVENTURE MONTESSORI LEARNING
details:
Adventure Montessori Learning, Inc.
offers an educational continuum from infants through the sixth grade. We offer a safe and nurturing educational environment in a Montessori setting. We believe, in our Montessori environment, that every child will become competent, confident, compassionate, and above all capable. We know that within each child is the seed of unlimited potential which will guide that child into adulthood. In our day care center as well as our private school, we emphasize an individualized educational experience as opposed to a strict “one size fits all” based education. At AML we utilize many different modalities to teach and achieve our developmental and educational goals.

Recent research shows that at least 80 percent of a child’s brain development occurs by the age of three. It further suggests that as much as 30 percent of a youngster’s brain capacity can be lost without a nurturing early environment that encourages learning. At Adventure Montessori we believe that the most important years of a child’s education are not high school and college, but the first six years of life. As a result, Adventure Montessori regards infant and early childhood education as the very foundation of everything that follows. Our goal is to treat each student on an individual basis producing self-discipline and a life-long love of learning.

At Adventure Montessori, each child is educated in accordance with their own rate of development. Our focus is to continually stimulate each individual student through an enriched educational environment consisting of activities, materials, and extensions that promote experimentation at every developmental level. Our school proudly features an orchard, vegetable gardens, and our very own animals. Following the the philosophy of Dr. Maria Montessori, we believe, as she did, that within each child is the seed of unlimited potential, that simply needs to be nurtured, and allowed to grow at it’s own pace. So, in essence, we offer each child, the world on a silver platter knowing that the combination of our educational environment coupled with each child’s innate curiosity will promote independence, exploration, and creativity within each child.

name: SMALL WORLD LEARNING CENTER
details:
We are so happy that you have taken the time to visit the Small World Learning Center website. We are located about one mile East of Santa Fe and about one mile West of Broadway on Mineral in the Westview Shopping Center in Littleton, Colorado.

Small World Learning Center is a family owned and operated childcare center for children ages six weeks to six years old. We pride ourselves in the fact that we are not a “corporate” or a “franchised” daycare center. Working in larger corporate centers is where we began our careers and fell in love with child care. We learned so much from a select group of people and for that we are grateful. While the big corporate centers meet the needs of many, there are some families that need just a little extra care and love. Each family and child is different, with different needs. Not every child learns in the traditional style. Our teachers have the ability to design their classroom curriculum to best fit the needs of the children. This flexibility allow us to truly serve the community that we live in.

Small World Learning Center currently has four class rooms: Infants, ages six weeks to 12 months; Young Toddlers, ages 12 months to 24 months, Toddlers, ages 24 months to 36 months; Preschool / Pre-kindergarten ages 36 months to 60 months. The safety and happiness of the children in these classrooms are our priority. We understand that it takes a special person to work with young children all day and we feel we have selected the perfect staff. Each staff member is certified in CPR, first aid and universal precaution. Each teacher is expected to know each child individually. By doing this, our teachers create and teach a curriculum that suits the class. Our goal is to fashion an environment where the children do not even know they are learning because of the creativity and love that is shown.

We have competitive pricing and schedules. We are happy to offer several discounts to help our families during these tough economic times. In most case we can find a schedule that works well for each family.

Our facility is secure. The front door has an individual code for each family and staff member. All the outside doors are locked for the security of the children.

Our facility is designed with large classrooms; this enables us to have plenty of space for learning centers and nap time. Our staff is thoroughly trained in the daily and closing routine of the center, so that, we can offer you a clean and inviting environment.

We look forward to hearing from you. Please call and schedule a tour today.

details:
Gan Chaya Preschool is a State Licensed Preschool that is devoted to top quality childcare and education. The preschool offers a uniquely warm & nurturing environment for children between the ages of 2 & 5 years old. 

Our Philosophy reflects current thinking in the field of early childhood education and aims to build a strong foundation for all future learning and living.  Each child’s individuality is valued and nurtured. as the curriculum is focused on encouraging your child’s developing sense of self. Parents are regarded as partners in the important role of raising children to be caring, responsible and creative Jewish adults. Through holiday celebrations, social functions, parent conferences and weekly newsletters, your family becomes a significant part of the community.

Our teaching staff are qualified and experienced professionals in the field of early childhood education. Our teachers share a genuine passion for the care and education of children and strive to create a warm and stimulating classroom environment.  

Our curriculum is built on an interdisciplinary approach to learning.  Subjects such as language arts, math, science, social studies and Judaic studies are integrated and emanate from a central concept or theme. We develop our most powerful themes from the Jewish and American holidays, family, community and nature.  During the year, additional themes emerge which reflect the interests of the class. The cognitive, physical, social, emotional, spiritual and creative domains of child development are the cornerstones of curriculum planning at Gan Chaya Preschool.

name: MOUNTAIN MONTESSORI AVON
details:
Mountain Montessori is a school founded by a dedicated group of Vail Valley parents.  In 2004 this group sought out Martha Teien and invited her to direct a new Montessori program, based on their past experience with her as a Montessori Educator.  In a matter of months the founders were able to find the right location, raise enough funds, and donate their own time to create a primary school for their children and the children of the Vail Valley. 

These founders and their director, wanted to create a school that provided exceptional early childhood education for Eagle County children.   They believed the way to accomplish this was to:
    Build a school with excellent teachers who were passionate about their work and about the children
    Create stability for the children by having the same teachers each day versus different teachers on different days
    Provide a classroom and playground that promotes learning, creativity, exploration and responsibility 
    Take care of our teachers by treating them as real teachers and not as just as care givers, provide a work environment that allows for balance of life, and encourage yearly  professional development in order  to promote commitment and longevity of tenure
    Finally, the founders believed strongly in Martha Teien's philosophy of allowing "What is best for the child?" to continually guide the school.
     

Mountain Montessori would like to recognize Alice Ruth, Ron Alvarez, Michele Evans, Patti Hardenbergh, Glen Davis and Matt Shapcott  for their faith, generosity and personal investment.  They worked incredibly hard to make an idea they had in the summer of 2004 become a reality in November 2004.  Thank you to our founding Board members!
